snippet.textDisplay:
Allow me to suggest an unexpected choice;

Mk4-6 VW TDI, specifically the Golf or the Jetta SportWagens...

Mk4 uses a 1.9 ALH turbo diesel, the 1.9 has a reputation of being utterly bulletproof, engines easily last 400,000+ miles before any work is needed

Mk5-6 use a 2.0l turbo diesel, only 140 HP, but 236 Ft-Lb torque all available below 3,000 RPM, a very torquey motor, great for surface streets and back roads

The Mk4-6 have fully independent suspension all around, and handle great for an economy/family car, they’re just plain fun to drive :)
The 2.0 TDI engine is nearly as indestructible as the 1.9, early DSG automatics before 2010 were problematic, but the manuals are always solid

A small, fun to drive car with a torquey engine, amazingly reliable ENGINES (transmission and electrics can be potentially a little “fussy” but that’s par for the course for a German car) and on top of that, they can get from 33-50 MPG, depending on conditions/ engine type/ how much fun you’re having, the 1.9 gets better mileage but the 2.0 puts out more power

Neither one uses AdBlue/DEF, the AdBlue system was introduced on the Mk7 models, you also get 10 more HP, but you lose the Independent rear suspension and get a more primitive twist beam rear axle (to make room for the AdBlue tank :( )

I’ve got a ‘12 Mk6 Golf TDI and I love it

The Golf’s suspension setup is also closer to the GTI, the SportWagen TDI has a little softer suspension setup than the Golf TDI though...

The Mk4-6 have fully independent suspension all around, and handle great for an economy/family car, they’re just plain fun to drive :)
The 2.0 TDI engine is nearly as indestructible as the 1.9, early DSG automatics before 2010 were problematic, but the manuals are always solid

A small, fun to drive car with a torquey engine, amazingly reliable *ENGINES* (transmission and electrics can be potentially a little “fussy” but that’s par for the course for a German car) and on top of that, they can get from 33-50 MPG, depending on conditions/ engine type/ how much fun you’re having, the 1.9 gets better mileage but the 2.0 puts out more power

Neither one uses AdBlue/DEF, the AdBlue system was introduced on the Mk7 models, you also get 10 more HP, but you lose the Independent rear suspension and get a more primitive twist beam rear axle (to make room for the AdBlue tank :(  )

I’ve got a ‘12 Mk6 Golf TDI and I love it

The Golf’s suspension setup is also closer to the GTI, the SportWagen TDI has a little softer suspension setup than the Golf TDI  though...

snippet.textDisplay:
Predicting which cars will be valuable is very easy, he gave the answer in the beginning of the video. Look at what is popular with teenagers today, that is the car that will be worth a lot of money in 15 to 20 years when they can buy it.

So that ugly Subaru crossover will never be worth anything. Your mom's Dodge Caravan or any minivan or crossover will never be worth anything. This is because they are not popular with today's teenagers, they are considered dull, boring family cars.

The Nissan GTR, yes. The Hellcat, yes. The Honda S2000, yes. The 2013 GT500, yes. (Also consider it is the last Shelby that Carroll Shelby was alive to have input on, and the last manual GT500. And there's only four thousand of them left. you can get a good one for around 38,000 right now. They will eventually skyrocket in price.)

When baby boomers were teenagers they loved the old Camaros, Chargers, and Mustangs. They increased in value when the Baby Boomers came of age.

The Mark 4 Supra and the M3 you mentioned were very popular with teenagers in the 90s, now they are worth a lot.

Again, if today's teenagers considered it boring, it will be worth nothing in the future. If today's teenagers like it, it will be worth something. There is your answer.
